                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/1523: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-01T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 1, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>112. Reference is made to your No. 123 of April 27, 6 p.m. Can it be rightly
                    supposed that the counterproposal which the British are making to the French is
                    not likely to be accepted? Could you state whether the committee in London has
                    considered the idea of rewording the March 1 Bases of Agreement so as to limit
                    the laying down of tonnage rather than to limit completion of tonnage? Under
                    this plan the agreement would terminate in July 1935. You may know whether such
                    an arrangement has been considered. I would not wish you to appear to offer any
                    such suggestion, as of course I cannot tell whether such an arrangement would be
                    feasible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
